getElementById() access HTML element with given id name
- <h1 id="title">Main title</h1>
  const mainTitleElement = document.getElementById('title');

Regular Expressions (regex) match specific characters in a string 
- const regex = /hello/;
- \s can be used to match any whitespace character 
- wrapping in [] turns into character class so those characters are ignored regardless of order 
  - /[helo]/ : ignores h e l and o intead of only helo
  - [0-9] matches all digits 0 to 9
    - \d shorthand character for all digits
- flags added after the second /
  - g tells pattern to continue looking after it finds a match : /hello/g
  - i makes character case insensitive
- use input.replace(regex, "") to remove characters from input string
- + modifier allows matching a pattern that occurs more than one time 

string.match() takes regex argument and returns array of match results

template literals allow interpolate variables directly within a string, dneoted with backticks ``
- variables passed in to template literal by surrounding the variable with ${}

the querySelectorAll() method returns a NodeList of all the elements that match the selector.
  - nodeList is an array-like object, access the elements using bracket notation.

innerHTML property sets or returns HTML content inside an element
button.addEventListener('click', printName); : printName function calle when button is clicked
insertAdjacentHTML takes two arguments
  - first argument is a string that specifies the position of the inserted element
  - second argument is a string containing the HTML to be inserted

for (const element of elementArray) {
  console.log(element);
}

alert() function built in to browsers to display pop-up message to user
- message to display passed as argument

Number() converts value to number, NaN if conversion not possible

e commonly used as argument to represent an event listener

string.toLowerCase()
Math.abs(num)
